    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Dorsally flattened with eight shell plates articulating dorsally, surrounded by a soft fleshy girdle. Shell plates are almost V-shaped with a lifted middle area sinking to the sides, then lifted on the lateral edges again. Texture of shell often eroded. If not, many flat, radiating ribs on the side areas and faint punctations on the rest of the plate. Girdle narrow and leathery with fine spinelets, cupped spicules and scattered tufts of spicules between the smaller spinelets. The articulamentum has wide, rounded anterior extensions. Colour grey or brown/green.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_6145",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Large, typically around 60-150 mm total body length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_6146",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> South Africa and Mozambique.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Saldanha Bay (Western Cape) to Jeffrey’s Bay and once found in Northern KwaZulu-Natal.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_6147",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Under rocks and boulders in sand in intertidal zone, common on flat rocky reefs, often sand-covered in the subtidal zone.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_6148",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Herbivorous – catches dislodged algae such as kelp.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_6149",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>External fertilization, pelagic trochophore larvae metamorphizes and settles as juvenile chiton.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_6150",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>This is by far the largest South African chiton and<strong> </strong>one of four South African species in this genus, but the only one present in the Western Cape. Other than the distribution and the large size, bunches of spines, as well as foveolate shell texture, separate this species from the others.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_6151",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Ashby, E (1928). South African chitons, being a description of the Polyplacophora represented in the Turton Collection. <i>Proceedings of the Malacological Society of London</i>, 18 (2), 76-92. (p. 82, pl. 8, figs 22-24).<br><br>Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa (Fourth edition). Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 162). <br><br>Kaas, P & Van Belle, RA (1985). Monograph of living Chitons (Mollusca: Polyplacophora). Vol. 1. Order Neoloricata: Lepidopleurina. E. J. Brill/W. Backhuys eds. Leiden 244 pp. (p. 110).<br><br>Kilburn, RN & Rippey, E (1982) Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg, xi + 249 pp. (p. 138, pl. 33, fig. 5).",
